5|$|This {{argument}} {{is based in}} part on the U.S. Supreme Court decision in the case of United States v. Bevans. In Bevans, the parties argued over whether a federal court in Massachusetts had jurisdiction over the case of a U.S. Marine charged with a murder that occurred on a ship in Boston Harbor. No issues regarding federal income taxation or the <b>Internal</b> <b>Revenue</b> Code were presented to or decided by the Court in the Bevans case. The <b>Internal</b> <b>Revenue</b> Code and the <b>Internal</b> <b>Revenue</b> Service did not yet exist in 1818, when the Bevans murder case was decided.|$|E
